— Bubblegum 

I vividly remember standing under these lights and stunning colors of the North! It was -48° and I took about a dozen photographs because I was in shock.

My nostrils were struggling to keep from freezing shut and blinking was a task. My clothes would freeze in place and to move, it felt like breaking the mold of a stiff straight jacket every other second.

My tripod legs froze and moving the camera around was near impossible. Within seconds of leaving the warm vehicle, I would re-freeze again.

In the early 1900’s the Holy Lights of the North made their way to Navajoland. My great grandmother saw the lights and recounted a short story of her experience. I was a little kid and never forgot her description of it.

Nothing has influenced my desire to see the Holy Lights of the North more than her story. Like grandma, I have a hard time describing the lights too.

Their beauty and movement are like waves moving across the sky. Coming from the land of red earth, these colors are the opposite of what we see daily.

In 2014 we had a daughter and I named her Aurora Winter only because of my great grandmother and her story. She now carry’s a Holy Light. We mostly call her Bubblegum.

I cannot wait to take Bubblegum up North and have her experience and see what her great, great grandma once saw. It’s a special connection she’ll always have.

#NorthernLights #Aurora

— Steady

This is probably one of my favorite coyote images I’ve ever taken. The entire sequence of the coyote walking along the waters edge, sledding on its belly on the hillside and walking on logs to get from its sleep place to another.

The coyote was awakened by ducks and swans around the bend. Fortunately I spotted the coyote snuggled up in the -15° weather.

As much as coyotes can be bothersome, they do teach me much about resilience during tough times. I’m always amazed at seeing nature in their normal element while I’m completely bundled in gear for the arctic!

In all, consistency and being steady seems to pay off when looking for a meal. The thing I love about the winter are the stories of the coyote that go back to the time of creation.

#Diné #WinterStories #Coyote #Trixter

— Baa hózhǫ́ǫgo niʼdizhchį́!

The very first time Denali and I went on a camping trip was when he was almost 4 months old and we were gone for a week.

I still remember him snuggling up to me in the wee hours of the morning.

A short time after he was born I walked outside in the middle of the night and gave a sincere prayer of gratitude. He was a beautiful baby boy and immediately after my prayer, I saw a shooting star. I’m not sure what that means however it’s part of his welcome to our lives.

He is such a beautiful boy. He is ridiculously smart with kindness unmatched. He is tremendously caring, someone to have fun with and sincere. He’s never talked back, loves to help and as much as I could say about him, he makes parenting easier than I see other boys his age.

I feel beyond blessed to be his father. At times we hang out like he’s my little brother because I never had brothers. The fun factor is often high and though he’s in 4th grade, not a day goes by where we don’t get a hug from him.

His cute freckles and long eye lashes match how sweet his soul is.

I cannot wait to see what he thinks when we see orcas in the wild and how luscious Iceland is. One day, we’ll swim in Hawai’i and most of all, continue to have more experiences than gifts.

He is Denali, the Great One. Shí yazh, our son. Happy Celebration on your Day of Birth ❤️

— Gems from the Past

I love this photograph because it covers the entire range of light within the histogram. In addition to that, I was paying heavy attention to the income storm ensuring the peaks would be visible. It wasn’t until I got home and imported the file into @lightroom that I noticed the Eagle flying directly into the storm.

In my cozy home office I wondered where the Eagle came from and more importantly, I wondered how the heck I didn’t see it until later.l back home.

While moving things around my new home office, I found rolls and sheets of film. I don’t know where my portable light box is at to view the exposures however, the snow packed mountains through my window gave plenty of light to review the gems of the past.

Using film has given me one massive advantage when it comes to photography and that is the ability to wait and most of all, appreciate the light through the various zones.

I’m so stoked to get organized because once that’s done, I cannot wait to be behind the couple of film cameras again.

There’s something unique, personal and like a gamble, hoping you were dialed. The truth of your attention and craftsmanship show only later when the film is developed and processed.

That moment is a true teacher which shows yet again, gems from a past experience.

Yesterday is gone. Today is a new day and soon, we will all be walking into a new year. May we be taught by the Eagle, that at times the only way to get over the mountains and storms ahead of us, is to fly right through that mother 🤐!

Then one day, look back and see how far we’ve come. One wise man once said “Give me this mountain…” — IYKYK

— A Little Bit of Light

When one looks at up at night, they may or may not see the stars. Our eyes can only accept so much light to then translate that reception into something we know. As I look up at night I see our Winter Stories, a way to be guided and ultimately, the Great Beyond where our Elders and ancestors roam. When the sun sets for me, I will meet them there.
 It is incredible how little a star is when compared to the space it occupies. It only inhabits a minuscule  piece of space amidst the Heaven’s. Likewise, a little bit of light in a home can illuminate a home and one’s soul.

I once pledged to find (creative) ways to power every single home so that our people can use that power to improve their lives, especially the youth who are the future problem solvers.

As much as that is a considerable goal, we continue to proceed with @goalzero and @heartofamerica to address education equity. Our partnerships are growing with others who have a similar vision. In short, I can’t wait to share what we’ll be doing in March and thereafter.

For now, we continue to #PowerAnythingAnywhere and when the lights are combined, they seem to be as stunning, moving and beautiful like the Milky Way. Just like the Holy One who once placed the corn pollen in the Heaven’s long ago, there is a path on Mother Earth and a the reminder is above in Father Sky.
 As we wrap up this year, may you plan the path you want to walk in the next. May you find inspiration and clarification from above.

— The Tree

I remember my paternal grandpa praying during Christmas. I was a kid and so antsy to rip open a few gifts. I recall sitting there in agony, impatient and hoping he would be done any second.

Then he started to thank the Creator for the plants, wildlife, the creatures that crawl, the birds that fly, those living in the water and the things like shrubs and wild grass which fed our animals.

Later that day I asked him why he thought of praying for so many things and he responded that there’s a lot that goes into things like trees and during Christmas we should remember all that goes into what we have under the tree during this season.

Over the last couple of years we’ve shifted away from having a lot of gifts and having more experiences. We’re still pursuing this goal and we’ve had so many more memories than things rotting away.

While leaving for our Christmas breakfast this morning, I saw a hawk sitting and resting. I immediately said “Aho Grandpa! Merry Christmas!!” and I cried a little.

I’m grateful for the many Christmas’ I’ve had. There were plenty with little gifts and a few where jobs were well had throughout the year.

As I look back now I better understand what gratitude meant to grandpa. They were well defined in his long prayers. He seemed to appreciate things much more than what was below the trees.

Merry Christmas ✨

— Ahéhee’

As I look back at this past year, it’s one packed with a commitment I made last year around this time which was to do more things I’ve never done before or don’t do on a regular basis.

I got to bike pack 400+ miles with my friend Josh for 5 days, visit Iceland, Banff and dodge a hurricane.

Vancouver, Baltimore and Red Mesa were meaningful by helping students have better resources for their education.

Buying and using an electric truck to install solar kits across Navajoland was wild which heightened the lack of infrastructure.

It seems every day became more valuable than ever before.

I have many people to thank, especially my wife Lauren for continuing to believe in me. Denali for how helpful he is and Bubblegum for being the life of the party!

I want to thank you as well. I’m grateful this app allows me to share what I think is important, critical and at times, silly.

I am so grateful for my brand partners for their support, paychecks and friendships!

We all have a story of some kind to tell and I want to thank you for following along with mine.

2023 will be filled with building our two cabins, more experiences with our kids, loving deeper and realizing even more at some point I will end up 6 feet below ground. I have a few things I want our kids to remember for the rest of their lives and my goal is to live longer than my grandpa who lived through 104 winters.

Thank You for being part of this year. May you solve more problems and develop or strengthen your character to help more people. I will too…

Ahéhee’ — Thank You 🫶🏽

— Outfoxed

I vividly remember sitting in 2nd grade escaping a tough day in boarding school through a book about foxes. I sat wanting nothing but to be home with my family just like I read in the book.

Not long ago I heard the boarding school was being torn down. I was happy because I wanted some memories of abuse, neglect and punishment buried with the building and in addition to that, I was saddened because of the great times there.

Hearing late news of the construction crew on-site, I left Salt Lake City and drove the 854 mile round trip to generate some photos of my childhood days.

While there, my memory without any mishap took me directly to that 2nd grade classroom. Oddly, the entire school was quiet and a few teachers were fixing their rooms.

Miraculously, I found the same book on foxes and my childhood pencil drawings of a heart were still in the book.

I asked to buy the very book I held 30+ years ago for $5. I was told it was “school property”. After multiple wagers, I asked if $250 would be fine.

“It’s government property” and can’t be purchased. I was outfoxed once more. Fortunately I was allowed to move a desk in the same orientation my childhood chair was in and I took a photo holding my favorite book of my youth. (Swipe)

One day I will get a stunning photograph of a fox. I simply know I will because the fluffy, nimble creature helped me escape mentally, while other kids physically ran away or tried to run home. Unfortunately I had incorrect settings of this fox from a recent trip. Next time my good friend — next time…

— Hanging Around

In my home office I have a single quote on a sticky note from a couple years ago. I’m surprised it’s still on my iMac after it’s been moved multiple times. I guess good words stick with you for a while.

As time continues to tick away, another variation has come of those short however yet powerful words.

At some point in the recent few years, the realization of moving into the next world hit me and has never gone away. It too reminds me of the endless ticking of Father Time.

That reality check has then spiraled into greater happiness, an increase in creativity and above all, additional (abundant) time with my wife, Denali and Bubblegum.

The sticky note reads “Do the things you normally wouldn’t.”

Within one week of moving into our new home, I turned on my iMac more than I did all of last year. The previous basement office felt like a dungeon and it was the last place I wanted to be to get my writing, photography edits, new projects and potential ideas off the ground. Yet, I invaded the comfy living room couch and kitchen table which weren’t the place for photography gear, hard drives, zoom meetings and the plethora of USBC cables.

There are a few things I don’t like doing and moving is one of them. Fortunately we’re near the tail end of having a somewhat organized home. Moving has also spawned a variation of the OG sticky note.

“Do the things you don’t want to do as fast as possible so you can play as much as possible.”

Lately, I’ve been biking a bit more because something fun, important and quite challenging is happening in April. I’m grateful that sticky note hung around and has been the secret sauce to my best days and what I believe will be the most meaningful year of my life.

@thule @thule_adventure @fezzari_bicycles

— Power Anything Anywhere

I remember the very first day I got a loaner road bike. I wore regular shorts, running shoes and rode in a mountain bike helmet. That was last year…

I’ve since bought appropriate gear and that’s made a massive improvement in enjoying the ride. That first day we went for a 42 mile stroll and I was stiff as a board for the next 3 days! It was hilarious to try and walk up or down the stairs!!

In April of last year Josh (@7tenths) and I bike packed 400 miles to raise money for a non-profit, camp and enjoy all that come with biking across the land with a little uncertainty.

One thing I take everywhere is one of my @GoalZero batteries. We have one in our kitchen, each vehicle and I always pack my Sherpa 100AC on flights.

I love the Venture 35 & 75 because both are waterproof, have built in LED Lights and when biking 40, 100 or 400+ miles, they pack really well and recharge all I need.

I’m now building out my fat bike to bike pack into the mountains for a couple days. It’s something I’ve never done and it’s constantly on my mind because I think I’ll see so many beautiful things. Nature is quite a classroom!

#PowerAnythingAnywhere #SolarPower #Fezzari

— To Be Continued…

I remember the morning hike was bright, colorful and oddly, well below freezing. My apps, watches and all things smart stopped working and my digital camera battery began to drain as I created a few photographs from this outing.

Hiking a few miles with a digital and large format camera, I was exhausted until I came across this scene. Fortunately the light was beaming as it often is and I took advantage of the break.

While watching the sun rise higher and higher, a thought nestled in about continuing on. I believe I am capable of so much and how I value the use of my time is a matter of making a few big decisions each day.

I’ve been working and burning some of the cliche midnight oil and can’t wait to share what’s new on Thursday.

The work continues and the goal remains… to do things I normally wouldn’t. On Thursday, I’ll let you know what I’ve been working on lately.

For now, may we rise like the sun and share the light we have with those around us. They too might be tired in their own way, of which, you may bring the rest needed.

To be continued on Thursday…

— Trailblazer

I’m reaching the point where I’m saying no to more ideas, projects and to things that may be a hindrance to my health. Though not yet perfected, I can see progress.

While perusing through my gallery and magically finding a password to an older PC, I found this gem of a lone wolf.

It resembles some of the things I do however not fully transpires my view. Reaching the point of having staff, a team or to sub-contract some work out is the direction I’m heading. Slowly finding my pack and not my marketing tribe…

If I had a Christmas work party, it would have been one where I’d be the only participant however giving my wife and family zero credit would be an absolute mistake. They too are beyond well deserving. Their support means everything to me. It’s the single intangible thing I’ve asked Lauren to provide because that belief lacked before. It’s amazing when someone provides their support. It makes a tremendous difference.

A lone wolf, probably using its senses to find its place in nature and it’s next meal, it goes as a lone wolf. Filled with endurance and many accolades, it looks back to more than likely see if I was still there. Visually, maybe it gave one last look to where it came from as it meanders forward into the great unknown.

Though much of the work I’ve created has been solo, I’m so excited about sharing with you tomorrow something I’ve been working on.

As much as it may be simple and providing a more formal presence, it took a lot of work all alone.

Tomorrow at 9am MTN I’ll share with you what I’ve been working on.

I hope it’s a reminder to check off something from your to do list and better yet, another example of doing the things you normally wouldn’t… in my case, 3-4 years!

#Wolf #Trailblazer #Monochrome

– Take 20

I’m beyond happy to share my new website with you at www.mylofowler.com which is now live. I’ve gone through countless photographs from the past 20+ years and selected some of my favorites and I’m doing my first ever 20% off sale! (Use code: “TAKE20” at checkout)

I’ve never discounted my work in the past because I would use proceeds from the orders to do my humanitarian work. Every dollar matters when powering more homes.
 Having a website for the past couple of years rotting away like a banana was always an eyesore!

I was recently asked what I enjoy about photography. There are some monumental aspects of it. It does provide for my family and if you’ve ever bought anything, I cannot say thank you enough.  One joy I always get is seeing photographs of mine hanging in places around the world. I find no greater satisfaction of the craft than seeing the end result find a new home.  I started learning how to make prints in the darkroom long before ink jets, light jets and the digital aspect. Seeing a handmade print come to life is an absolute testament of the craft.

With the advancements of technology, I’ve taken what I learned in the darkroom, past mistakes and love how it has streamlined the process from ordering to delivery.

So if I’m in Iceland, riding our horse or on a photography assignment and you make an order, @smugmug will take care of you and your order will be shipped in a matter of days even while I’m doing other things.  If you’ve ever wanted a print of mine, use the code “TAKE20” at checkout to receive 20% off. This discount ends on January 22, 2023.

T’áá íiyisíí Ahéhee – Thank you very much.
 Mylo

— A Sliver from the Silver Lining

There’s no doubt I’ve got my (fair) share of responsibilities, goals and head trash where at times, I wonder if I’ll ever make it out or achieve what I’d like.

When looking for this image, the only file of it existed on an old PC computer I was using in 2015. After a million tries on the password path, I struck gold! I was able to login and see a lot of my work from the early years. No need to the thoughts, recommendations and comments about backing up my work. Done.

Through that process, I recalled the scientific evolution of how WD-40 was born. Hint, 39 formulas didn’t work to displace water.

I thought about the somewhat common quote of Edison “Our greatest weakness lies in giving up. The most certain way to succeed is always to try just one more time.”

I love personal development audio books, podcasts and literature. If you’re in the mood, I highly recommend both of @davidgoggins books. If you can stomach the brutal truth of where you’re at, you’ll run through a wall!

I’m so glad I came across @edmylett - I have his books and his latest one titled “The Power of One More” is immensely moving.

While finding this exposure in my files of old, it’s probably one of the best experiences I’ve ever had.

It is absolutely amazing how beautiful even just a sliver of light is. Maybe in the real contrast of life sometimes surrounded by darkness, hot damn… a little bit of light makes a beautiful difference.

There are many examples of those who gave it just one more try. Ask your parents, especially your grandparents. You may not find greater motivation from many than from those of who you come from.

This photograph reminds me most of how much a little light can change it all. Now, go kick some major ass!

I included this image in my new website where you can still get 20% off til Sunday by using the code “TAKE20” — discount code only usable at www.MyloFowler.com

Please don’t give up whatever is challenging you! I’ve got some weight too!

Mylo

— Getting Up, Facing East

I absolutely love being back home. Many gyms are packed as basketball games are going on and fans go nuts for their teams. Most teams and fans are often from really small communities.

With somewhat of the isolation and rural life, each member of the community is important and also seams to be known by all. Greetings take place as family and friends meet… so much happens around sports. It is quite uplifting to see the word Ké live in a beautiful way.

The unfortunate reality is some schools, families, facilities have a head start which I believe is ok.

That makes the drive to compete even more meaningful and even more rewarding, when kids from a reservation or from the middle of nowhere, accomplish what they do.

The process is always a damn fight for Indigenous youth and families. To compete, play at competitive levels, and to fit into the social community under the Heavens.

I share these insights with our family so we can understand how much of a privilege we have, that one leg up.

While waking up and facing East, I pray I may use my day to help someone. Quite oddly, I’ve also heard similar prayers coming from those that have had very little.

Amidst not having much, deep in their hearts they had all the room, more immense than space itself, to love, lift and share.

“Today, I will walk out. Everything unnecessary will leave me. With beauty all around me, may I walk…”

The prayers of my grandparents have become mine. Their way is simple, profound and peculiar. Today I got up, faced the East. Tomorrow, I hope to do it again.

Overlanding is beyond having a cool truck and gear to be in remote places. It’s how I deepen my roots which began when a piece of my umbilical cord was placed back in the earth the day I was born.

This connection to our Holy Mother Earth is key and what I seek. Simple and profound.

@thule_adventure

– The Balance

While rearranging my home office I had to unplug my grandpa’s radio. Once the shelving was in place I plugged the radio into the outlet again.

The not so clear reception of an AM or FM radio station was a perfect connection to the nostalgic days of my youth.
 While rotating the dial to find an oldies station, the slight movements gave an explicit result of the frequencies coming in.
 So much can be learned from this simple action to dial in… a constant quest to find balance.

Though my own grandparents now roam the next world, our beautiful clan ship allows me to call other Elders grandpa and grandma again. To be called grandson these days is quite priceless.

She Nali Dan has endured his 93rd winter. What a soul. What stories he has. Later this year he plans to help spearhead a multi-day hike. He’s mastered the 25+ mile route without much of today’s available gear.

He simply goes with little due to his impressive knowledge of the natural springs and ability to navigate the numerous veins of canyons. 
Getting a call from his son Ray yesterday was beautiful. I accepted the invitation to join the experience.

Knowing I can always use some minor adjustments, I hope to bask in Dan’s songs about the balance.

— The Visit

A couple of years before my paternal grandpa journeyed into the next world, he shared stories about that place.

I was a kid and deep within me, my heart was pounding and eventually, I started to cry fervently.

I couldn’t imagine being here without him. He put his well worn callused hands on my neck and gave me a hug. With a little chuckle in his speech, he said it’ll be ok.

He then said he’ll visit me from that world. You have no idea how much comfort that gave me!

Being in boarding school, I got to see my mom on the weekends. Every now and then, her work took her to Kaibeto where I was.

My lil Mylo heart was crushed knowing my mom was somewhere in that building within eyesight. Many times I just wanted to see her, even if it were for a mere few seconds.

For her, that was a 118 mile round trip for work. I’m beyond grateful for her grit, sacrifice, love and unmatched will to provide for us. Somehow we managed to leave the food stamp world and get on our own… I love you mom! Just seeing you still makes my heart so happy.

Grandpa said when I needed strength, power, wisdom and even an occasional kick in the ass, he’d visit through an Eagle.

If he wanted to give a quick hello and wave to me while I was on my journey, he’d fly by as a hawk. A swift, beautiful surprise!

I randomly tweaked my back about a week ago. Standing to brush my teeth is now a task and I’m about ready to remove my shoestrings and replace them with Velcro straps! Taking clothes on or off below the belt looks like I’m trying to be sexy with the sloth like slow movements… it’s far from looking attractive.

I wonder if grandpa is aware of my back pain because the past few days, we saw a handful of incredible eagles.

I love these visits because they always happen when I most need them. I do not know how it all works except that it does.

Ahéhee’ (Thank You) Creator for the blessing of a long life after this short one. Ahéhee’ for a spiritually sweet, rugged, wrangler grandpa. Most of all, ahéhee’ Creator for shíma (my mother). She is the pinnacle of love.

The Visits… I’m grateful for them. They give me strength. This print is now available on my website — a visual reminder.

— Light

In the last 10 days I drove a bit over 2,400 miles in the Rivian to test the truck in temps below 0° and to deliver more solar kits to power more homes in March.

Amidst the busy schedule and daily belief of only one life to live, I love and need Sunday’s. It’s the day I set aside to look back at the Light I absorbed. I review the week to see if I got too much or not enough.

Being Mormon or in proper terms, a member of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints is a unique path. It has its beautiful aspects and certainly, the needed growing pains within the faith are necessary.

I asked my sweet parents and grandparents why I was led to this way and not theirs. Having medicine men and women as my examples of those trying to walk the way of balance and beauty was a pure blessing because of how genuine and simple they lived with a purpose to obtain that balance we call Hózhó.

I find that what I’m taught to be at church is what they were without much lesson planning or manuals. They simply were incredible living examples of my youth and I draw from them to strengthen my faith.

I miss my home congregation because when you enter the chapel, some of the sweetest people of all creation sat there. Regular attendees and visitors were always given a warm handshake or my favorite, a heartfelt hugs. Any and everyone was always moved by that.

I miss their smiles and the regular “Yá'át'ééh shíyááááázh— Hello My Child…

My elders simply said there’s a reason the Light is asking of you. Go and find out.

Through prayer and deep sincere pondering for Denali, Bubblegum and I, the Light has led me through the wilderness of life. A few years ago on this day, with a quivering voice, knee deep in snow, I asked Lauren if she would marry me.

She’s been the Holy Light of our family — our matriarch. A completion to have Hózhó, even during the storms.

— The Call

The past week was incredible to meet with our non-profit team and help pack another 1,000 education packs for students in the heart of Navajoland.

In addition to helping kids have school supplies they need, each received a grade appropriate book. The authors, illustrations and writings are Indigenous People.

While in awe of all the contents of the education pack I paused for a moment and reflected back on my favorite childhood book of my youth.

The book was about foxes.

Several years ago I got wind that the school I was in was going to be demolished and parts of it were going to be updated.

I left our home in Salt Lake and made the 16 hour round trip. My hope was I could find my classrooms and take some photos.

The Saturday was quiet and then from some kind of stored memory I walked right into my second grade class.

The old red dictionaries were STILL being used and familiar posters were still hanging. I then asked the teacher if she had any books about animals.

She guided me to a half dozen books and like a miracle, I found my favorite book.

It wasn’t a copy. It was the actual book I drew two hearts in. The larger heart represented my mother and the smaller one was for lil Mylo.

I asked if I could purchase the book and was declined because “it’s government property…” — I was shocked so I asked if I could take a photo of myself holding the book (swipe).

After 20+ years, there was no way I could buy the book that was my escape. Boarding school had its great and terrible moments.

The book about foxes got my mind to wonder and day dream of a better place to be.

Since picking up a camera, I’ve seen a few foxes in absolute rural Alaska, Yellowstone and back home. My family will tell you I’ve made many trips to simply set out and return with a few exposures.

It wasn’t until today I was able to take the photographs I’ve always wanted!!

The meaning is sooo deeply rooted and gosh, they remind me of how much healing can be found and experienced in nature.

I’ve added two of these images to my website. I cannot wait to print these and simply smile.

In our language we call them “The Ones Who Call for The Morning”.

– The Sliver	

It’s cloudy and overcast today in Happy Valley. Quite gloomy and not so vibrant. I enjoyed the constant drizzle of rain we’ve been getting overnight. With the power going out for a few hours late last night while restarting Ted Lasso, many options were eliminated and the focus was turned to the simple things.

I remember the first time going to bed in Huntington Beach after I moved there. I slept on the floor and woke up. I ran to CVS for some basic things like toothpaste, tp and some shower stuff.  On my return people were frantic and lost. I was curious what the heck happened - the power went out.  With sleeping on the floor and having no power, I was in my element while others were foreign to the experience. I lit some candles and saw the ceiling flicker away from the flame. I remember sleeping so well that night!

At the time I had about $200 to my name. I wasn’t stressed because I believed big things would happen. I wasn’t doing well spiritually however I made the move from Colorado to PCH following an answer to a prayer. Deciding to add a sliver of light, I began anew spiritually.
 I made a lot of friends and like usual, kept a couple close to the vest after many years. (Rhi Rhi, talking about you!) 

While my time in Huntington was amazing, 9/11 also took place. I recall exactly to this day where I was and the clothes I was wearing. Red Carhardt, Wolvering Steel Toed boots and my lunch too.

As I look back on some tough even dark and gloomy times, I’m always amazed at how just a sliver of light can illuminate various things from my soul, apartment and now photographs.
 I’m not sure how it works however the Light always comes during the tough times. What I do know is that it works. I thank the Creator for the Light, even at times when it’s faint, it is profound and always casts out darkness.

Last nights power outage was a good reminder to know where the light is.

#PowerAnythingAnywhere @goalzero

— Drowning

While on photography assignments, I FaceTime or call home at odd hours due to the story we’re after. Last night while talking with Bubblegum (our daughter) I reminded how impressed and proud of her I was.

A few months back some kids in her class and school were making fun of another girl simply because her name is Juniper, just like the tree.

This finally stopped when Bubblegum stood up and put an end to the mess. When she told me what she did, she had some tears because she was slightly afraid of what others may say.

I recall kneeling down and looking her in those beautiful brown eyes, and reminding her she is smart, a friend anyone would love to have, and above all, brave for standing for what’s right.

I told Bubblegum her example strengthens me when we face big challenges, issues and being firm when it’s time to stand up for others, especially the ones who can’t speak, like nature.

Today, our Tribe has a case that lands in the Supreme Court about water rights, use and management. For so long, our voices have been intentionally muted, removed and unheard.

Breaches of Treaties will be reviewed and today we begin by being a voice for the water that has flowed through the Sacred Mountains, untouchable by its people since English words were written.

Today we begin speaking for our living relatives — the elk, badger, sheep, bobcat and wildlife. Today we speak for the corn, sage brush, peaches and even the Juniper.

Water is used with caution due to its limited availability, contamination and distance needed to travel to obtain the water.

For so long, many who’ve come after us have had the right to vote, speak, legislate and access water while we forcibly stand aside, shackled in silenced, drowning in useless Treaties.

I’m beyond grateful for Bubblegum reminding me to use photographs, even from an iPhone submerged in a trough of water, to speak for what is right.

The Diné way of Hózhó, balance, is what we seek. When we speak for water, it extends far beyond us, the Holy Five Fingered People.

Water Is Life — too many waste it in the West and we’re coming for it. We’re tired of drowning in broken promises.

It denotes and emphasizes the meaning of family.

Our Elders and the Wise Ones often have the highest reverence of a relative, which often isn’t based on blood quantum or birth certificates.

The spirit of Ké is far from removing someone from their ancestral homelands, however yet, inclusive of the fold.

When we introduce ourselves, the translation would be “Hello my relatives and my people.” It emphasizes family, belonging, kinship, respect and many adjectives revolving around the word humanity.

Thank goodness for Ké. Without it, would the work be as meaningful?

— Grand Entry

Bubblegum recently gave a talk about miracles. She asked for more details about a few I’ve had on road trips, in Southern France as a Mormon Missionary and others in the red rocks of the Southwest, especially back home on Navajoland.

I recall going to bed early due to a long day of work in the sun as a photography guide. Then around 2:15am I woke up in haste.

My vision was so clear that standing on a ledge to feel the updraft of the morning brisk air woke me in my sleep. I also saw the stunning colors of dawn.

The dream was as if I was there. I dwelt on those thoughts so much that I prayed for clarification.

Following the prompting, I packed my cheap tent and camera gear. Running low on 4x5 large format film, I only packed one holder loaded with film on each side.

Off I went with two chances.

My friend and I camped and we spent the evening talking away in our language. Laughing and eating some frybread with mutton ribs, the temperature began to drop as the stars began to rise.

Mesmerized, a shooting star lit the night and the soft wind picked up. Snuggling deeper into my sleeping bag, I fell asleep.

A 5am piss break woke me up and I opened my tent to a layer of fresh powder… it snowed!

I wondered how and above all, I didn’t see any headlights or trails of dust below in the valley.

A phone call later would confirm the muddy roads required canceling school and tours.

The valley was quiet, cleaned of any floating particle and I was above it all on a ledge underneath the dark cloth waiting to start counting… one one thousand, two one thousand…

Eight seconds later, the panoramic print Grand Entry was created on film.

The title of the photograph reflects on the beautiful, vivid morning I saw in my dream only the night before.

After the aperture closed on my lens I reflected deeper on the Grand Entry I made into this, the Glittering World, a time ago.

My dear mother was all alone. The panoramic photograph and baby Mylo were born on this day.

Grand Entry… What a miracle… Chasing a dream.

To me, I felt at peace and was inspired by the sponsors and supporters. The dark place they thought they were in illuminated my world!

I was so amazed at the decisions many made to become better for it. They were so focused on The One. Whether that was their Divine Figure, the one change or improvement they wanted, I was amazed at the one thing they did differently.

When we would meet again we would no longer be strangers yet fellow humans who were trying. The peace brought into the round circle became special to me.

After I felt I was back on my feet, I drifted away. Today, I thought of the group. Isn’t it amazing what one change or a sliver of Light can do?

I was not prepared to view my compositions flipped vertically and horizontally (swipe to see what I mean… that’s how I saw all my compositions for many years behind my large format view cameras)

As luck would have it, after buying a 4x5, lenses, film holders and all the gear required, my trustee Pentax gave up the ghost — it stopped working right before my first photograph!

Fortunately, I had my countless experiences with the light of the Southwest. The ombre shadows and lively sunsets of fire, the range was stunning!

The true test came when the moment came to put playtime to rest and expose my first sheet of film, drawing from my field notes which were in a desk at home.

I remember being soo thrilled in the instant, yet the process was so simple. The only sound in the vast desert was that of a 2 second shutter being released.

No magic. Simple, pure and nothing required batteries.

The season is at hand to start my photography workshops again.

Helping photographers, new and experienced, is one of my favorite things to do! If you’d like to join me, send me a message.

— The Timeline

When hardships come by my own doing or from others, I try to take a step back and look at the moment in life.

Time and challenges immediately after my divorce felt like it was never ending. I wished for the pain to flee and then through equine therapy, I realized my viewpoint had a massive impact on facing the challenging times.

Drawing a parallel I reflected on a childhood science ah-ha/woah moment to realize the moment would soon flee and the night would pass.

Again, if earth were the size of a grain of sand, the size of our Milky Way Galaxy would be over 28 million miles wide!

This makes the known universe overwhelmingly massive!!!

I like this visual because it helps me understand in the timeline of my existence, the tough and hard times in my life are but a speck at most!

As I look at photographs of Bubblegum from pre 3 years old, we spent a lot of time in nature. It’s where I felt the most calm and peace.

It was a tough time that now seems so long ago. The tough days too shall pass and are a fleck relative to the timeline of our existence, both physical and spiritual.

We often say if we wake up, that’s a beautiful sign the Creator isn’t done with us, yet.

Have a wonderful week my friends.

— Sounds

Our home in Arizona sits a couple miles away from my parents house. As a kid I spent a lot of time outside and spent as much of it with my awesome brothers and sisters (cousins for most of you). In addition to extended family members, I learned from the voices of my beautiful elders, namely my grand parents and wonderful great grandmother.

As the seasons change shinálí hastiin (paternal grandpa) would teach me the sounds in nature. From migrating birds, deer, foxes and the occasional hoot at night, his hearing was acute.

Unfortunately, he’d ask me to ride one of his horses to where our home is now, because he could hear chainsaws, the opening of a trucks 4 barrel carburetor and essentially, someone being somewhere they shouldn’t.
 Having sheep, cows, horses as a small version of a ranch with bucking shoots, he also taught me much around livestock which he oversaw for our family and eventually our community as the Grazing Committee President.

Every Summer was a blast because we branded, tagged, spayed, neutered and got western with the hot and sticky days of branding. Getting kicked in the shin by cows was the worst! Grandpa was truly the kindest and toughest!

He also took time to teach me the sounds of the animals. How to tell when they’re looking for their young, in destress and the range of their emotions.

Drawing on sound behind the camera, I whistled deep inside Canyon De Chelly and this mustang came running! Disappointed in seeing it was me instead of a competing stud, he stopped and we had a stair down.

I remember the sounds of his hoofs and flaring of his nostrils after exhaling ricochet off the towering sandstone canyon walls.

You know where I’ll be when the leaves begin to change. Hopefully, we see and hear each other again.

— Words

My sweet mother has a couple sisters. Some never got to grow up as they’ve lived in the World of Great Spirits. On Mother Earth, she has one sister and since my youth and into every new day, I called her shimá (mother) too.

We have wonderful nieces and nephews and I love how my older sister taught them what to call her…shimá as well. Above that, she has her sons call her shimá regardless of where they are.

Stealing and loving the teaching, our kids (Denali & Bubblegum) call me shizhé'é (father) in front of their friends, at church, soccer practice and anywhere else.

In our language shizhé'é and shimá mean something waaaay more than simply mom and dad. Likewise, our greeting of Yá'át'ééh could take an hour or two to fully understand how such a word has deep roots!

To be candid, I’ve said more bad words this year than use the words “but” and “just”. In most cases I realized anything coming after the use of those words is either me defending or minimizing the context.

The words became useless several years ago when my phone rang and someone asked “who’s calling you?” I replied “it’s just my mom”… 

From our Diné teachings, I’m learning more and more how powerful and beautiful certain words are. Likewise, attempting to describe the path of the Holy People of the North (that’s what we call them as they’re known as the Aurora Borealis), words escape and you simply have to see them. Words in describing the experience seem to be useless too.

This unique image hangs in Bubblegum’s room because my great grandmother described to me how she saw the Holy Path in the early 1900’s and that’s why Aurora Winter is our daughter’s name even though we mostly call her Bubblegum.

The Pathway is heading South and while hours above Fairbanks in -48° weather absolutely alone, I connected with my great grandmother again. Hopefully someone made an offering and sang songs like she did for them Above… I recall sharing a few words in a prayer for Their long journey somewhere South. Navajoland is a ways away.

— Twin Warriors

Long ago there was a time when darkness, negativity, hostility and evil swept across the land. Those within the Four Sacred Mountains and the Male and Female Rivers endured a troubling time.

Many didn’t know how to overcome the time and two young boys set off on a journey to Jóhonaaʼéí, the Sun.

As a source of Light and power, the young men also endured much and accomplished all that was necessary. From there, they returned with a phenomenal ability to communicate and use sacred Lightning to defend the darkness.

In my youth I did a lot of crazy ish! I once shaved my head and left lightning bolts above my ears. Inspired by Mr. T and Shaq, I proceeded a few days until my great grandma talked to me and shared the story of the Twin Warriors. Immediately after I buzzed the bolts off and learned a wonderful lesson.

She went onto say in that same week the teachings about earth being a medicine cabinet and that “we are each others medicine” too.

My twin nephews just had their birthdays and I was reminded of the Twin Warriors. Their lineage is a powerful one!

Not long ago I knelt in this slot canyon waiting for light to split into two beams.

From it I draw the hope that when faced with challenges or obstacles, they only block a small portion of our capacity and with determination, we can continue to be a light for others.

The only title I could give this image pays homage to the brave Twin Warriors of our people. Without the light being blocked, the composition wouldn’t be as magnificent. Likewise, acknowledging the challenges and rising above it, is where we shine.

Twin Warriors… dumb hair ideas and a couple humble teachings from my great grandmother Sarah. Share what light you have no matter how much you have. It always casts out darkness. Always…

— Hats Off

The very first time I saw wild horses was with shinálí, my paternal grandpa.

I may have been in 3rd or 4th grade. What I remember most was trying to find our horses for a week. We started early and ended late in the evening every day. I’d never seen anything move so fast across the sagebrush filled sand dunes, rocks and the terrain of the land.

Our family’s fastest horse was an Arabian/Mustang mix however in the chaos of being spooked, even our fastest horses were in the middle or tail end of the herd!

It was an absolute riot as my imaginations of riding a horse as fast as possible were born then. After many days of chasing the wild horses including ours, we finally managed to corral about 75 horses! I’d never seen something so rugged, mangled and beautiful!

It was the only way we could separate our horses from the wild ones.

Early the next morning we met at the arena only to find our horses and a blazed trail. All the horses were let out during the night. Tire tracks would indicate someone made a visit while we were snoozing away.

My grandpa was frustrated because he wanted to study the horses, their conditions and see the stallions of the herd.

He then turned to his coveted mustang Pony. Pure, wild, stern and unstoppable, I instead opted for the thoroughbred/quarter horse named Brownie.

After nearly a week of running from us, it was time to take part in a ceremony. I’ll never forget starting the ride and ending 55 miles later. Of the many horses that started, only three made it to the end. Two were grandpas and I rode one.

His tender care, study and companionship was the first time I saw loyalty. What I recall the most was his support in my hopes to ride in the ceremony.

I’ll never forget him saying how well I rode Brownie. From grandpa, we both received a treat. Brownie got her corn mix and I got a cold Coke with mutton stew.

I’m packing for my next NatGeo assignment going West. I hope to see wild horses. I’ll tip my hat to them only because that’s what I saw grandpa do too.

— The Wise Ones

I was absolutely tired from driving for 29 hours and my older sister asked if I could take a 4 hour detour. Wanting to be home in my bed and a warm shower after being on the road to audition for “Finding Nemo”, I turned off and headed towards Canyon De Chelly.

Getting my gear and hoping this grandma would make it in time for sunset, we were really cutting it down to the wire. The Four hour detour for less than 3 minutes of sunset light?

The truck pulled up and I was ashamed. I was embarrassed within and regretted all the grouchy feelings I had before.

She was carefully and delicately helped out of the truck with a portable step stool, family on both sides holding her hands, she sat and briefly talked about how she saw the canyon and landscape change for nearly a century.

Not knowing who I’d be photographing aside from “a beautiful grandma”, I found out just before the trucks arrival it was my older sister’s biological grandmother.

That’s when my heart broke. I mentioned needing to find a filter in my truck (lies…), instead I wiped my tears away.

Those few minutes with her are still engrained in me because that’s the greatest lesson I learned in under a couple minutes with someone.

Sometimes that’s all it takes to help them and we’re often the better for it because we did something we normally wouldn’t. What a feeling.

When I got home I was happy to know Disney loved my voice over so if you watch “Finding Nemo” in Navajo, you now know who “Crush” is.

Most of all on that trip I found a better part of me.

With the temperatures dropping, I can’t wait to haul firewood with my dad for a few grandmas and grandpas — The Wise Ones. Now days minutes with them are ever precious, even if they aren’t my grandma or grandpa.

— A Little

Every now and then I’m asked if I have a favorite photograph. This image called “Sweet Light” is one of my favorites because of the experience I had 8 years ago on this very week.

Just prior to creating the photograph, we delivered pallets of drinking water to many, many families who were affected by the Gold King Mine Spill. The water turned into the same color as the seasonal pumpkin spice of whatever, yet it was toxic, harmful and disgusting.

As the anniversary of that incredible trip comes around again, I’m reminded of the subtle and minute changes that aren’t seen, the little things.

— The One

Across my readings, audio books and podcasts, I’m intrigued by how much of a difference those who are accomplishing a bit, all seem to carry the same denominator of making a single change at some point.

I’m excited to add a refrigerator to my Rivian R1T because it’ll force me to cut some plastic which once done, there is no going back. The result may force me to fill it with carrots, celery, sugar snap peas for Bubblegum and other better choices of snacks than chips or gummy nerds.

Without expecting much in return, she gave, gave and still gives. My input to have her slow down has been useless. She’s my ultimate example of giving because she still does.

One of her most profound teachings that will resonate with me into the eternity’s is “if you have one more, you can share”.

Anytime I see two similar features in nature, I am immediately drawn to my older sister. We both were fed, nourished and supported by a single mother. I’m not sure how we ever managed, we did because of the sweet grit of my mother.

— Dreams

The childhood home I grew up in is no larger than our current living room and kitchen combined.

The amazing trade was having a childhood backyard of trails, cliff edges and wildlife which is larger than the valley we live in now. Over 20 square miles of hidden gems, no fences and a dozen horses to ride!

What a difference.

I recall my father, uncles and his friends helping us build our home. I’ll forever remember the night he peeled back the blue 10’x10’ tarp from the unfinished roof. Dad on one end, mom and my little sister in between and I on the other. I felt special “protecting” mom and Tweet.

On 3” foam pads, I didn’t sleep that night because I could hear crickets, coyotes, bugs & every now and then I saw satellites wiz by.

I saw a shooting star and no kid felt luckier than me.

Soon, we were going to have our own home. It took a while to complete the house. I knew when it was payday because we always bought more lumber or building materials.

That 600 square foot home, though small, immeasurably massive as it was filled with love, challenges and hard work.

Middle school came. I recall starting my 7th grade year wearing clothes from prior years. Life and work was tough. I was the joke amidst my friends for wearing what I could.

Ultimately, I overcame a few days of taunting. Deep within, I was so happy because for the first time, I wouldn’t be sleeping on 3” foam pads.

We got bunk beds!

I recall it was a Saturday around 3pm, the beds were fully assembled and all I wanted to do was lay in bed.

After high school I lived off PCH a couple minutes from the pier in Huntington Beach, CA.

My first night in the apartment, the power went out in the city and I slept on the floor.

I couldn’t feel any more comfortable with a flash light in hand surrounded by frantic people without electricity and running water.

My parents visited our house a few weeks ago and I’ve never seen my mother so happy.

The little Mylo in me came out and I showed her what we had and that our house is a 24/7 extension of my childhood castle.

Every now and then I sleep on a 3” foam pad in my roof top tent. Again, a level of comfort to sleep so soundly.

Dream big they said…

— Everyday

Today we honor each other. Our introduction as Diné people is unmatched. We begin by saying “Hello my relatives and my People”.

— Summits

I’ve always been fascinated with space, stars and lights in the sky. Most of that curious comes from many nights sleeping outside in my youth. Whether that was sleeping in a tree house, truck bed or in a tent, I lost track of time counting satellites, shooting stars and seeing odd things move around above.

I’ll also never forget the time we tricked my mom to turn on the lights in our house. She wasn’t aware that the electricity was actually working in our house.

She being a fun sport, flipped the switch expecting nothing, the lights turned on and she froze. In awe and amazement, she said “this weekend we’re going to buy a microwave!” It was funny and our lives changed a lot from that day.

We stopped buying single use batteries, propane tanks and replaced our two lightbulbs with LED’s. This all happened about 20 years ago and I believe those lightbulbs are still lighting up my parents home!

As much as life has improved for our family, many are still left without and we’re progressing to minimize the canyon of being online with power.

My incredible friends at @goalzero is giving our non-profit partner @heartofamerica a Yeti 1000 for every purchase of a Yeti 1000 today! This buy one, give one will help you have the power you need and help others on a daily basis too.

I use our Goal Zero yeti batteries to charge my devices, lights, cotton candy maker, grill, cameras and so much more.

Living with a power source, whether that be grid or solar power, has made a tremendous impact on my life.

To help or learn more, visit the link in my bio on this #GivingTuesday — Like a telescope pointing to a star, together, we can bring that light and power much closer to those without.

As cool as it is being on summits of mountains, nothing is greater than being on a roof empowering the next generation for humanity.

— Joy

I have a new 500+ mile bike film coming out and hopefully soon, it’ll be viewable. The ride was about a crucial visual regarding the chance to overcome real tough times, making challenging and scary decisions and ultimately, about joy. It’s what lasts.

During this time of the year, happiness sneaks its way into our homes through the medium of gifts, thoughts and what lies beneath a thin layer of wrapping paper.

During this time of year, the slot canyons back home receive a special kind of light that isn’t found during the other seasons. The slot canyons is where my attention to exposure values began. In addition to that, it’s where my career started by asking a lady if she’d like some help with camera settings.

The result of making some adjustments on a big-digital-camera (3 megapixels), was her hitting the review button and saying “holy shit!” because of what she saw. Not a second later, other photographers asked what settings she was using and she said something I’ll never forget, “Ask Mylo! He’ll set you up!!”

That simple result was something I was terrified to do. Intimidated by many with lenses and expensive gear, I was timid in asking if someone would like help.

Doing so, changed the absolute trajectory of my life, career and purpose of existence. Again, a very scary decision to commit to figuring out light.

During this time of the year, we hang lights on our tree, gutter and deck. As I see the lights change colors, they create a beautiful visual.

One year my father surprised us by coming home from work in Indonesia. The flight from Phoenix to Page flys overhead, close to my parent’s home.

I recall lighting up our roof on the hogan, without design, hoping my father would see our little home from the airplane. While setting up the lights, a few lights weren’t working and if they didn’t work, the entire display was non functional.

I never forgot that because we all have light. Together, we create something beautiful.

When my dad got home, he said he could see the house from a ways above. May we see the Light in each other and help brighten the dim ones of others, not only in this season however every single one to come.

That is Joy.

— High Light

I grew up with the teaching of running and its many benefits including the oneness with our provider, Mother Earth.

From running after sheep, horses and partaking in ceremonies like the coming of age or even through our 12 acre fields of food, my favorite was running to our tree houses!

I’m beyond fortunate to have incredible childhood friends. In high school I had an absolute love/hate relationship with running. Hate because of the pain and constant competition of our varsity team and the love of brotherhood, teammates and again, the oneness. No time outs, referee’s or even substitutes, it was an all out effort to perform from the start.

Ultimately, I loved cross country because its what helped me graduate! It was the motivation to keep my grades up in order to participate in sports. Together, we won State every year to continue the deep Running Devil roots of the boys from Page.

Fast forward a couple decades and running is still deep within us. My good brother, Shaun Martin, led us through tough races and was the example of running to me. He is an incredible example of doing good. In his community, it is rare to go anywhere and not have people thank him or say “Hi Mr. Martin!!” The respect he and his wife Melissa have in the heart of Navajoland is beautiful as they empower the next generation of students as Principals of two schools. Both also started the Canyon De Chelly 55k Ultra in 2012. A run that sells out within seconds allowing 150 runners to join.

Since the beginning we’ve been using more @goalzero lights and batteries to power the start/finish line, aid stations and first aide equipment.

This year I brought two of the new Sky Lights to help with lighting before the sunrise. No generator or anything noisy. Quiet to have the oneness.

I’m hoping the use of the portable 12’ Sky Light at a bus stop in New Mexico so kids are visible while waiting for the bus.

I’ve had many highlights around running and am happy to have run the 55k back home in Canyon Desert Chelly. What a place to be one with the land and light.

When traveling through, please be careful of livestock, bus stops and especially our Elders often driving slow.

— Impact

On a cold, star filled night back home on Navajoland 11 years ago, Denali was born. Today we celebrate his special birthday with prayer, the ultimate breakfast, gifts and what we love about him. Denali’s light is so special to us! I’ll feel it 4,000 years from now.

— Shake Things Up

I’m researching routes, charging stations, camp spots and checking my list twice for an upcoming trip.

I’ve had many memories from past roadtrips to reflect on. When Denali was 3-4 months old, we set out on a 10 day trip. I packed so much and still remember a few details. We redid that same trip when he was able to stand on his own.

Another trip I recall, which I recently got more details on, was when we stopped by a windmill in the middle of nowhere. I was around 1st grade and my father had won the bull riding event. He won a few hundred tough bucks and we washed at the windmill to prep for a ceremony. Photos of those are in my mother’s album.

I also recall the very first time we packed everything we needed about 35 years ago, we took so many backroads in our 84 Chevy with a camper. I spent the entire time in the back since I had the freedom to bounce around and not be confined to a seat.

Occasionally, we’d stop and I’d emerge from a man cub made tornado! I’ll forever remember, dang near Lion King style, my father drove to a summit. I recall feeling like a marble in a sardine can through the “HANG ON” shouts!

Dad took me to a point and we looked across a beautiful valley. I’d later realize it was Heber, UT. Without much pavement in our route, it was pure overlanding without today’s version of the genre. In my youth I fell in love with the valley. Living there for a moment was a no brainer and I can be in that valley within 45 minutes!

We had everything we needed back then for the weeklong trip. 

While I spot wildlife in the harsh winter of the Rockies, I am amazed at all they have, which isn’t much. Most of all, I fall deeper in thought of the (ancient) ones well before us and how they survived in balance with our relatives of the wild.

This Bald Eagle was quite comfortable while I shook in -22° weather! Thank goodness for downed jackets, insulated boots, fast shutter speeds and quite a few pixels to have the flakes of snow in detail!

Soon, my @sonyalpha gear will shake things up in some real cold weather. I’m so stoked for 2024!!

— Dreams & Pinky Promises

My first camera was a big deal. Broke with a dream, it was the first time I dedicated myself to something and created a specific savings account.  The feeling of exploring, hiking and waiting around for whatever light was all I wanted to do. My friends and I saw a lot of the Southwest. Some moved on and I stayed in our little 4 stop light town. I got paid to play in the dirt and be surrounded by the Eden for landscape photography.

A high profile client came to town with a beautiful family. They wanted portraits and oddly, I got the invite. Understanding what they wanted, I recall telling them two things.

One, they needed someone with a digital camera, not me with a 4x5 view camera. The other was a photographer from Vegas or LA. I was up front and told them I couldn’t fit the bill because I was proficient in photographing rocks, trees, dirt and water, not people.
 The gentleman from the Middle East then said calmly with confidence “You may be right about these however, everything is possible. Most of all, you and your people are from here. This is your land. Someone else won’t know the terrain and light. Where can you get a digital camera?”

I said “the nearest one is probably in Phoenix.” He then said something I’ll never forget.  “Well, it sounds like we’ll see you tomorrow morning. Put the camera on my bill too.”  I said ok and I hauled butt to Phoenix full of energy and stoke!

Fortunately the same place I bought my first camera (large format view camera) was restocking late into the night.  I know I could have indulged in the latest however I made a modest choice; a Nikon D700 with the kit lens. It worked to create their photographs and the family was happy!

By early February nearly 80% of the New Years resolutions made, will have met the end of their journey.

The first two images are from my first wildlife trip with that D700, a 2-3 minute encounter with a stunning fox from the early 2000’s. The last two images are from a recent fox with the latest and greatest from Sony.

Keep the Pinky Promises and Keep Dreaming. They may get you somewhere meaningful. A modest start is always worth the go!

— Drifting

I’m grateful to have instant access to 2023 because of the galleries and library of memories on my phone and online catalog of images.

As much as this app shows some of those moments, none can ever portray the gratitude I have for the three other souls I love most.

I often take time to reflect and have deep thoughts about the size of our known universe. Challenges, tough times and even the wins are a speck of time.

I absolutely love this because the hiccups, setbacks and heartaches are but a moment so minuscule that I continue to inhale breathes of hope, positivity, happiness with a little bit of hell yea!

I share much with you and on a larger scale even more with our kids of my surroundings, childhood and at times, appropriate difficulties.

Being human is an eternal gift. The odds of being here are so much to one, yet, I sometimes forget that alone is worth the gratitude I should feel each fleeting moment of the passing sun.

Another revolution around a fireball was made and all I can say about this upcoming year is it will be filled with so much pressure, performance and passion.

Unfortunately, many misuse the word passion using it in a positive, living my dream, kinda way when it is the absolute opposite filled with suffering, fear, aloneness, doubt, do I matter?, is this worth it?… not quite the word to use synonymously with “living life to the fullest…”

My father once said “every now and then you have to have holy shit moments!” That’s when you know you are entering a realm of greater self discovery, internal expansion and growth.

May you all have a year you want and may it be filled with more holy shit moments as you grow, explore (not just in nature or on a trail) and above all, learn more about those who have opposite beliefs than you. Doing so will only test the veracity of your foundation while building a greater level of empathy for those who believe differently than you. That could be what unlocks the true test of humanity and unite us on why we are even here, drifting in an eternal space.

Happy New Year my fellow mammals.
